#   BE-007: root out ROWS; serialize ULOGā†’HUNK via a plain utility fn

ROWS (`dog/ROWS.{h,c}`) is an unnecessary typed subsystem ā€” 195 refs across 18 files
(`rows`, `rows_row`, `ROWSnav`, `ROWSdiscipline`, `ROWSOpen/Close/FeedRow/FeedRec`)
ā€” for what is just serializing a ULOG event sequence into ONE `H` hunk as a token
stream. Replace it with a single utility FUNCTION in HUNK or ULOG, with NO new data
types (operate on existing `ulogrec`/`hunk`/`u8b`/`u8cs`). Delete ROWS entirely,
repoint every caller, and restore correct verb output. It is also currently BROKEN
(bannerless hunks get rebased into per-row labels ā€” the POST-022 wreckage). This
REVERSES and supersedes [BE-005] (and the ROWS wiring its children [POST-018]/
[GET-026]/[STATUS-001] landed); it subsumes [POST-022].

##  Input

### Context
ROWS adds types and a builder for a job that is one serialization function.

 -  Real job: a ULOG row `(ts, verb, uri)` ā†’ tokens appended to ONE hunk (the
    `<date> <verb> <path>` table with per-column toks + a hidden nav URI per row),
    flushed via `HUNKu8sFeedOut`. No state object is needed.
 -  Callers (18): sniff/{LS,GET,PATCH,PUT,POST,DEL,SNIFF.exe}, dog/{ULOG,HUNK},
    keeper/{WALK,KEEP.exe}, beagle/BE.cli, + their tests.
 -  Currently broken: ROWS rows emitted with no active table become empty-URI hunks
    that `HUNKu8sRelay` rebases to the mount path ā†’ a bare label per row ([POST-022]).

### Goals
Delete ROWS; one utility fn; identical (correct) output.

 -  Add `HUNK`/`ULOG` utility that serializes a ULOG event (or a slice of them) into a
    hunk token sequence ā€” NO new types; nav scheme passed as a plain param/`ron60`,
    not a `ROWSnav` enum or `rows_row` struct.
 -  Remove `dog/ROWS.{h,c}`; repoint all 18 callers to the utility fn.
 -  Verb output (status/post/put/get/diff/ls banners) byte-correct; the [POST-022]
    per-row-label / full-history wreckage fixed by construction.

### Constraints
 -  ABC idioms; NO new data types. Keep the per-column toks + hidden per-row nav URI
    behavior via fn params, not a struct. The tty-stream vs one-hunk `--tlv` modes
    come from `HUNKMode`, already global.

